{"id":"Braden_calculation.v0.0.5","gdl_version":"2.1","concept":"gt0001","language":{"original_language":"ISO_639-1::en"},"description":{"original_author":{"name":"Shweta Prasad Ghaisas","email":"S.Prasad.Ghaisas@cambio.se","organisation":"Cambio CDS","date":"2025-05-24"},"other_contributors":["Therese Lindberg"],"lifecycle_state":"Author draft","details":{"en":{"id":"en","purpose":"To calculate the total sum for Braden score.","keywords":["braden score","pressure ulcers","pressure sores","bed sores","friction","shear","activity","movement","risk","sensory perception","moisture","mobility","nutrition"],"use":"The Braden score is used in immobile or chronically hospitalized patients to identify patients who are at a risk of developing pressure ulcers.\n\nThe score is calculated based on six different areas: activity, moisture, mobility, nutrition, sensory perception, and friction and shear.\n\n5 input fields- activity, moisture, mobility, nutrition and sensory perception- have 4 grades with +1 denoting worst outcome and +4 denoting best outcome. The input field, friction and shear, has 3 grades with +1 denoting worst outcome and +3 denoting best outcome. These six areas form the input fields. Fill in all the input fields to calculate the total score.","misuse":"The score should not be used by itself, but should be used in conjunction with clinical assessment as it does not capture all risk factors of developing pressure ulcers. The score should not be calculated only once, periodic assessments are necessary.","copyright":"Â© Cambio CDS"}},"other_details":{"references":"Bergstrom N, Braden BJ, Laguzza A, Holman V. The Braden scale for predicting pressure sore risk. Nurs Res. 1987;36(4):205-10.","en":"Braden score identifies patients at risk of developing pressure ulcers."}},"definition":{"data_bindings":{"gt0017":{"id":"gt0017","type":"INPUT","model_id":"openEHR-EHR-OBSERVATION.braden_scale.v1","template_id":"openEHR-EHR-OBSERVATION.braden_scale.v1","elements":{"gt001